<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%" style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr>
<td valign="top" width="4%" style="TEXT-ALIGN: right">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: right; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">(1)&#160; </font></div>
</td>
<td valign="top" width="69%">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">Two of the ten leased aircraft were operated under capital leases. For further discussion, refer to Note 10, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">Operating Leases</font>.</font></div>
</td>
</tr></table>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><a name="FN2">2.&#160;&#160;Significant Accounting Policies</a></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(a) Basis of Presentation and Principles of Consolidation</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Pinnacle Airlines Corp. and its wholly-owned subsidiaries, Pinnacle, Mesaba, and Colgan, with the elimination of all intercompany transactions and balances.&#160; The accompanying consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States of America.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(b) Revenue Recognition</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Passenger revenues and ground handling revenues are recognized in the period the services are provided.&#160; Under the Company&#8217;s capacity purchase arrangements with Delta and United, the Company receives a fixed-fee as well as a reimbursement of specified costs with the potential of additional revenue incentives from its partners when the Company&#8217;s operational performance exceeds certain metrics.&#160; The reimbursement of specified costs, known as &#8220;pass-through costs,&#8221; may include aircraft ownership costs, passenger liability and hull insurance, aircraft property taxes, landing fees, and catering. &#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Under Pinnacle&#8217;s CRJ-900 Delta Connection Agreement (&#8220;Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA&#8221;), the Company defers certain revenue, primarily related to maintenance.&#160;&#160;For example, the Company receives monthly payments based on contractual rates per block hour for heavy maintenance activities not expected to be performed for at least a year.&#160;&#160;To the extent that the ultimate maintenance costs incurred are less than amounts collected, the Company will refund to Delta the excess.&#160;&#160;Conversely, the Company bears the risk that the maintenance costs incurred exceed the payments generated from the contractual rates.&#160;&#160;The Company defers the revenue related to these maintenance deposits, and will recognize the revenue when it performs the underlying maintenance services.&#160;&#160;Deferred revenue is incl
uded in the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheets, and also includes revenue related to the sale of the Company&#8217;s bankruptcy claim against Northwest, which is described in detail in Note 3, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Code-share Agreements with Partners.</font></font></div>

<br>
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>
</div>

<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>
</div>

<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; WIDTH: 100%">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">63</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%">
<hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
</div>
</div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">2.&#160;&#160;Significant Accounting Policies (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Because many of the Company&#8217;s expenses are reimbursable expenses, the Company&#8217;s major airline partners sometimes negotiate contracts on the Company&#8217;s behalf to reduce the reimbursable costs and maximize the economic benefits of an agreement.&#160; For example, during 2008, Delta negotiated an engine maintenance agreement which included maintenance on CRJ-200 aircraft within the fleets of some of its subsidiaries as well as Pinnacle and Mesaba.&#160; In situations where the Company&#8217;s major partner negotiates an agreement on the Company&#8217;s behalf such that the maintenance vendor is the primary obligor for the completion of the service, the Company&#8217;s revenue associated with these agreements is presented at the amounts billed for reimbursement net of the related expense incurred.&#160; Gross billings o
f $8,809, $8,566, and $11,162 is presented net of expense of $8,105, $7,881, and $10,269 in regional airline services revenue in the Company&#8217;s consolidated statement of operations for the years ended December 31, 2010, 2009, and 2008, respectively.&#160;&#160;The Company earns margin on this revenue, which is presented gross.&#160;&#160;For all other items, and except as described above, all amounts billed for reimbursement under the Company&#8217;s capacity purchase agreements are recognized as revenue on a gross basis.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Under the Company&#8217;s code-share agreements, the Company is reimbursed an amount per aircraft designed to compensate the Company for certain aircraft ownership costs. The Company has concluded that a component of its revenue under the Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA and Colgan&#8217;s Q400 United capacity purchase agreement (&#8220;United Q400 CPA&#8221;) is rental income, inasmuch as the agreements identify the code-share partner&#8217;s &#8220;right of use&#8221; of a specific type and number of aircraft over a stated period of time. The amount deemed to be rental income during 2010, 2009, and 2008 was $69,087, $65,125, and $30,961, respectively, and has been included in regional airline services revenue on the Company&#8217;s consolidated statements of operations.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company also earns revenue from its pro-rate operating agreements with United and US Airways, and under Essential Air Service (&#8220;EAS&#8221;) contracts with the Department of Transportation (&#8220;DOT&#8221;).&#160; Regional airline service revenues are recognized when flights are completed.&#160; Tickets are sold and processed by the partner airlines.&#160;&#160;Amounts due to the Company for completed flights and incentive compensation are settled on a monthly basis.&#160;&#160;Passenger tickets typically include segments flown by the Company and segments flown by the partner airlines.&#160;&#160;Passenger revenues are based on a pro-rated share of ticket prices earned by the Company for the passengers transported.&#160; The Company earns additional compensation based on the achievement of certain performance metrics.&#16
0; Revenue earned by the Company under its EAS contracts with the DOT is recognized based on actual flights completed to and from selected smaller cities and communities and is based on pre-determined contractual rates.&#160; In addition, one of the Company&#8217;s pro-rate operating agreements with United includes a guarantee fee provision whereby a payment is either made by or to the Company to the extent that scheduled block hours for any given month are higher or lower than the guaranteed block hours.&#160;&#160;For a discussion of the Company&#8217;s code-share agreements, refer to Note 3, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Code-share Agreements with Partners</font>.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(c) Aircraft Maintenance and Repair Costs</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>Aircraft maintenance and repairs, including planned major maintenance activities, are expensed as incurred because maintenance activities do not represent separately identifiable assets or property units in and of themselves.&#160;&#160;Rather, they serve only to restore assets to their original operating condition.&#160;&#160;Maintenance and repairs incurred under power-by-the-hour maintenance contracts are accrued and expensed when a contractual obligation exists, generally on a per flight hour basis.&#160;&#160;For certain leased aircraft, the Company is subject to aircraft lease return provisions that require a minimum portion of an engine overhaul based on the life of the engine at the lease return date.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(d) Capitalized Interest</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company capitalizes interest on assets that require a period of time to acquire the asset and prepare them for their intended use.&#160;&#160;The Company is currently capitalizing interest, as part of the asset&#8217;s cost, on its aircraft pre-delivery payments.&#160;&#160;For the years ended December 31, 2010, 2009 and 2008, the Company recorded gross interest expense of $42,499, $45,399, and $46,539, respectively, of which $1,688, $537, and $1,992, respectively, was capitalized.</font></div>

<br>
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>
</div>

<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>
</div>

<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; WIDTH: 100%">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">64</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%">
<hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
</div>
</div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<br>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">2.&#160;&#160;Significant Accounting Policies (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(e) Cash and Cash Equivalents and Restricted Cash</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>Cash equivalents consist of short-term, highly liquid investments, which are readily convertible into cash and have initial maturities of three months or less.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>Restricted cash consists of demand deposit accounts and other similar instruments with various maturity dates, all less than one year, and are used as collateral for standby letter of credit facilities that the Company maintains for various vendors.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2010 and 2009, the Company had restricted cash of $8,219 and $3,115, respectively.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(f) Financial Instruments</font></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>Fair values of receivables and accounts payable approximate their carrying amounts due to the short period of time to maturity.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>The Company invests excess cash balances into U.S. treasury securities and money market mutual funds investing in U.S. Treasury securities.&#160;&#160;In addition, the Company invests a portion of its excess cash in overnight repurchase agreements collateralized by U.S. agency securities at the end of each business day.&#160;&#160;The agreements represent an unconditional obligation of banks to repay principal and repurchase securities on the next business day. The overnight investment balance was $0 and $11,559 at December 31, 2010 and 2009, respectively, and is included in cash and cash equivalents on the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheets.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Company is required to provide standby letters of credit to support certain obligations that arise in the ordinary course of business.&#160;&#160;Although the letters of credit are off-balance sheet, the majority of obligations to which they relate are reflected as liabilities in the consolidated balance sheet.&#160;&#160;Outstanding letters of credit totaled $7,761 and $2,856 at December&#160;31, 2010 and 2009, respectively.<br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(g) Accounts Receivable and Related Reserve</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>The Company periodically evaluates and makes estimates of the collectability of its accounts receivable.&#160;&#160;Generally, the reserve for bad debt is determined using the specific identification method.&#160;&#160;The Company exercises judgment in assessing the realization of such receivables, and the Company&#8217;s policy is to continuously review the age and quality of its accounts receivable as one element of determining the approximate amount of revenue.&#160;&#160;In accordance with this policy, the receivable reserve was $85 and $213 as of December 31, 2010 and 2009, respectively.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(h) Spare Parts and Supplies</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>Spare parts and supplies consist of expendable parts and maintenance supplies related to flight equipment, which are carried at cost using the first-in, first-out (FIFO) method.&#160;&#160;Spare parts and supplies are recorded as inventory when purchased and charged to expense as used.&#160;&#160;Fleet retirement reserve for spare parts expected to be on hand at the date the aircraft are retired from service is provided over the remaining estimated useful life of the related aircraft equipment. In addition, an allowance for spare parts currently identified as obsolete or excess is provided.&#160;&#160;These allowances are based on management estimates and are subject to change.</font></div>

<br>
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>
</div>

<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>
</div>

<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; WIDTH: 100%">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">65</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%">
<hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
</div>
</div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">2.&#160;&#160;Significant Accounting Policies (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(i) Property and Equipment</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Property and equipment, consisting primarily of aircraft, aircraft rotable spare parts and other property, are stated at cost, net of accumulated depreciation. &#160;Expenditures for major renewals, modifications and improvements that extend the useful life of the asset are capitalized.&#160; Property and equipment are depreciated to estimated residual values using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets.&#160; Depreciation of owned aircraft and aircraft rotable spares is determined by allocating the cost, net of estimated residual value, over the asset&#8217;s estimated useful life.&#160;&#160;Depreciation of equipment related to leased aircraft is determined by allocating the cost, net of estimated residual value, over the shorter of the asset&#8217;s useful life or the remaining lease terms of relat
ed aircraft.&#160;&#160;Modifications that significantly enhance the operating performance and/or extend the useful lives of property and equipment are capitalized and amortized over the lesser of the remaining life of the asset or the lease term, as applicable.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana, sans-serif; FONT-SIZE: 1pt">&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The depreciation of property and equipment over their estimated useful lives, and the determination of any salvage values, requires management to make judgments about future events.&#160;&#160;Because the Company utilizes many of its assets over relatively long periods, periodic evaluations are performed to determine whether adjustments to the estimated service lives or salvage values are necessary to ensure these estimates properly match the economic use of the asset.&#160;&#160;This evaluation may result in changes in the estimated lives and residual values used to depreciate the aircraft and other equipment. These estimates affect the amount of depreciation expense recognized in a period and, ultimately, any gain or loss on the disposal of the asset.&#160;&#160;Property and equipment under capital leases are recorded at the lower o
f the present value of the future minimum lease payments or the fair value of the asset at the inception of the lease.</font></div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Estimated useful lives and residual values for the Company&#8217;s property and equipment are as follows:</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

</div>

<div align="center">
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="75%" style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr>
<td valign="top" width="3%" style="TEXT-ALIGN: right">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: right; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">(1)&#160; </font></div>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" width="56%">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><font style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">Depreciation is determined by allocating the cost, net of estimated residual value, over the shorter of the asset&#8217;s useful life or the remaining lease terms of related aircraft, as applicable<font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">.</font></font></font></div>
</td>
</tr></table>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(j) Long-Lived and Intangible Assets</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>The Company evaluates whether there has been an impairment of its long-lived and intangible assets when indicators of impairment exist.&#160;&#160;Impairment exists when the carrying amount of a long-lived or intangible asset is not recoverable (undiscounted cash flows are less than the asset&#8217;s carrying value) and exceeds its fair value. If it is determined that an impairment exists, the carrying value of the long-lived asset is reduced to its fair value.&#160;&#160;When considering whether or not impairment of long-lived assets exists, the Company groups similar assets together at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities and compares the undiscounted cash flows for the entire group of assets to t
he carrying value of the same group of assets.&#160;&#160;Asset groupings are typically done at the fleet or contract level.</font></div>

<br>
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>
</div>

<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>

<td nowrap valign="bottom" width="1%" style="TEXT-ALIGN: left; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4px"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;</font></td>

</div>

<div>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%" style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr>
<td valign="top" width="3%" style="TEXT-ALIGN: right">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: right; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">(1)&#160; </font></div>
</td>
<td valign="top" width="70%">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">The non-compete agreement will be amortized through June 30, 2011.</font></div>
</td>
</tr></table>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(k) Fair Value Measurements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company&#8217;s investments are required to be measured at fair value on a recurring basis.&#160;&#160;A fair value measurement should be determined based on the assumptions that market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability.&#160;&#160;As a basis for considering market participant assumptions in fair value measurements, accounting guidance establishes a fair value hierarchy that distinguishes between market participant assumptions based on market data obtained from sources independent of the reporting entity (observable inputs that are classified within Levels 1 and 2 of the hierarchy) and the reporting entity&#8217;s own assumptions about market participant assumptions (unobservable inputs classified within Level 3 of the hierarchy).</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In instances where the determination of the fair value measurement is based on inputs from different levels of the fair value hierarchy, the level in the fair value hierarchy within which the entire fair value measurement falls is based on the lowest level input that is significant to the fair value measurement in its entirety. The Company&#8217;s assessment of the significance of a particular input to the fair value measurement in its entirety requires judgment and considers factors specific to the asset or liability.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company invests excess cash balances primarily in short-term money market instruments and overnight repurchase agreements.&#160;&#160;Previously, the Company held auction rate securities (&#8220;ARS&#8221;), which prior to events that developed during the first quarter of 2008 that impaired the investments&#8217; liquidity, met the Company&#8217;s stated investment policy.&#160; Investments in marketable securities were classified as available-for-sale and presented at their estimated fair values based on quoted market prices for those securities.&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">At December 31, 2010 and 2009, the Company&#8217;s investment balance included options to repurchase ARS that it received as part of an ARS Settlement (the &#8220;ARS Call Options&#8221;).&#160; The ARS Call Options are reported at fair value, which is determined using a discounted cash flow model that assesses the likelihood that the underlying ARS may be redeemed at par or sold through a successful auction or in a secondary market prior to the end of the option term. At December 31, 2010 and 2009, the fair value of the ARS Call Options was $1,852 and $2,723, respectively.&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company is exposed to certain risks arising from both its business operations and economic conditions.&#160;&#160;The Company utilizes aircraft fuel call options and options to purchase forward interest rate swaps (&#8220;Swaptions&#8221;) in order to manage its commodity price risk and interest rate risk, respectively.&#160;&#160;The valuations of these instruments are determined using widely accepted valuation techniques, including discounted cash flow analysis on the expected cash flows of each derivative.&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">For further discussion, see Note 7, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Investments and Fair Value Measurements, </font>and Note 9, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Hedging Activities</font>.</font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<br>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">2.&#160;&#160;Significant Accounting Policies (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(l) Goodwill</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>Goodwill represents the excess of the purchase price over the fair value of acquired net assets.&#160;&#160;Goodwill in the amount of $22,449 was recorded in connection with Northwest&#8217;s acquisition of the Company in 1997.&#160;&#160;In connection with the 2007 acquisition of Colgan, goodwill in the amount of $9,785 was recorded, all of which became impaired and was expensed during 2008.&#160;&#160;For additional information, see Note 15,<font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline"> Impairment and Aircraft Return Costs</font>.&#160;&#160;In 2010, goodwill in the amount of $3,860 was recorded as a result of the acquisition of Mesaba.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2010, the Company had finalized the purchase accounting of the Mesaba acquisition, which is discussed in Note 4, <f
ont style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Acquisition of Mesaba.</font></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>Goodwill is reviewed at least annually for impairment by comparing the fair value of each of the Company&#8217;s reporting units with its carrying value.&#160;&#160;The Company&#8217;s three reporting units are Pinnacle, Mesaba, and Colgan.&#160;&#160;Fair value is determined using a discounted cash flow methodology and a market approach and includes management&#8217;s assumptions on revenue growth rates, operating margins, discount rates, and expected capital expenditures.&#160;&#160;The Company performs its impairment test of each reporting unit&#8217;s goodwill on an annual basis at October 1 and, if certain events or circumstances indicate that an impairment loss may have been incurred, on an interim basis as well.&#160;&#160;The Company determined that its goodwill was not impaire
d as of December 31, 2010 and 2009.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(m) Employee Health-Care Related Benefits and Accruals</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company is self-insured for the majority of group health insurance costs, subject to specific retention levels. Liabilities associated with the risks that are retained by the Company are not discounted.&#160; The Company records a liability for health insurance claims based on its estimate of claims that have been incurred but are not yet reported to the Company by its plan administrator.&#160; These estimates are largely based on historical claims experience and severity factors.&#160;&#160;The estimated accruals for these liabilities could be significantly affected if future occurrences and claims differ from these assumptions and historical trends.&#160; Additionally, the Company offers Pinnacle&#8217;s pilots limited post-retirement health care benefits, which are accrued over the service periods.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(n) Defined Contribution Plans and Other Post-retirement Benefits</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">401(k) Plans</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company maintains four 401(k) plans covering substantially all of its employees. Each year, participants may contribute a portion of their pre-tax annual compensation, subject to Internal Revenue Code limitations. The Company&#8217;s 401(k) plans also contain profit sharing provisions allowing the Company to make discretionary contributions for the benefit of all plan participants.&#160;&#160;The Company made the following matching contributions:</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Retired Pilots&#8217; Insurance Benefit Plan</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company&#8217;s Pinnacle subsidiary provides its pilots with health and dental insurance benefits from their retirement age of 60 until they are eligible for Medicare coverage at age 65.&#160;&#160;The Company is self-insured for these costs.&#160;&#160;The estimated future net benefit payments are immaterial to the Company&#8217;s financial results and cash flows.</font></div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">2.&#160;&#160;Significant Accounting Policies (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(o) Segment Reporting</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Generally accepted accounting principles require disclosures related to components of a company for which separate financial information is available to and evaluated regularly by the company&#8217;s chief operating decision maker when deciding how to allocate resources and in assessing performance.&#160;&#160;&#160;The Company&#8217;s three operating segments consist of its three subsidiaries, Pinnacle, Mesaba, and Colgan.&#160;&#160;Information pertaining to the Company&#8217;s reportable segments is presented in Note 5, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Segment Reporting</font>.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(p) Use of Estimates</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The preparation of the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States of America requires the use of estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities, the reported amounts of revenues and expenses, and the disclosure of contingent liabilities.&#160;&#160;Management makes its best estimate of the ultimate outcome for these items based on historical trends and other information available when the financial statements are prepared.&#160;&#160;Changes in estimates are recognized in accordance with the accounting rules applicable for the estimate, which is typically in the period when the new information becomes available to management.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(q) New Accounting Standards</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In January 2010, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#8220;FASB&#8221;)&#160;&#160;issued Accounting Standards Update (&#8220;ASU&#8221;)&#160;&#160;No. 2010-06, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Improving Disclosures about Fair Value Measurements</font>, an amendment to FASB Accounting Standards Codification (&#8220;ASC&#8221;) Topic 820, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures</font>.&#160;&#160;This amendment requires an entity to: (i) disclose separately the amounts of significant transfers in and out of Level 1 and Level 2 fair value measurements and describe the reasons for the transfers, (ii) disclose separately the reasons for any transfers in and out of Level 3, and (iii) present separate information for Level 3 activity pertaining to gross purchases, sa
les, issuances, and settlements.&#160;&#160;The new disclosures are effective for interim and annual reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2009 (calendar year 2010), with the exception of disclosures about purchases, sales, issuances, and settlements in the roll forward of activity in Level 3 fair value measurements, which are effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2010 (calendar year 2011).&#160;&#160;The Company adopted this guidance beginning with the interim period ended March 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;See Note 7, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Investments and Fair Value Measurements</font>.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;In September 2009, the FASB ratified ASU No. 2009-13 (formerly referred to as Emerging Issues Task Force Issue No. 08-1), <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Revenue Arrangements with Multiple Deliverables</font>.&#160;&#160;ASU No. 2009-13 will update FASB ASC Topic 605, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Revenue Recognition,</font> and will change the accounting for certain revenue arrangements.&#160;&#160;The new requirements change the allocation methods used in determining how to account for multiple payment streams and will result in the ability to separately account for more deliverables, and potentially less revenue deferrals.&#160;&#160;Additionally, ASU No. 2009-13 requires enhanced disclosures in financial statements and is effective for revenue arrangements entered into or materially modi
fied in fiscal years beginning after June&#160;15, 2010 (calendar year 2011) on a prospective basis, with early application permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact ASU No. 2009-13 will have on its consolidated financial statements.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In June 2009, the FASB issued Statement of Financial Accounting Standard (&#8220;SFAS&#8221;) No.&#160;166, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Accounting for Transfers of Financial Assets, an Amendment of FASB Statement No.&#160;140</font>, which amends FASB ASC Topic 860, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Transfers and Servicing</font>.&#160;&#160;This guidance requires more information about transfers of financial assets, including securitization transactions, and where companies have continuing exposure to the risks related to transferred financial assets. This guidance is effective for financial asset transfers occurring after the beginning of an entity&#8217;s first fiscal year beginning after November&#160;15, 2009 (calendar year 2010). The Company adopted this guidance on January 1, 2010.&#160;&#1
60;The application of the requirements of this guidance did not have a material effect on the accompanying consolidated financial statements.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><a name="FN3">3.&#160;&#160;Code-share Agreements with Partners</a></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company&#8217;s operating contracts fall under two categories: capacity purchase agreements and revenue pro-rate agreements.&#160;&#160;The Company&#8217;s pro-rate agreements are primarily modified pro-rate agreements, as they are designed to provide a level of financial support from partners beyond the pro-rated passenger revenue received under a traditional pro-rate agreement.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">100%</font></div>

</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Capacity Purchase Agreements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Under capacity purchase agreements (&#8220;CPAs&#8221;), major airline partners purchase the Company&#8217;s flying capacity by paying pre-determined rates for specified flying, regardless of the number of passengers on board or the amount of revenue collected from passengers.&#160;&#160;These arrangements typically include incentive payments when the Company meets certain operational performance measures.&#160;&#160;Additionally, certain operating costs such as fuel, aircraft rent or ownership costs, aviation insurance premiums, certain ground handling and airport related costs, and property taxes are reimbursed or paid for directly by the partner, which eliminates the Company&#8217;s risk associated with a change in the price of these goods or services.&#160; The Company earns additional revenue for costs reimbursed by the partner d
ue to the contractual margin or mark-up payments added to the reimbursed cost when the Company invoices its partner for reimbursement.&#160;&#160;Conversely, while the Company bears no risk of price fluctuations for costs paid directly by the partner, the Company also earns no additional revenue related to the contractual margin added to reimbursed costs.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company provides regional airline capacity to Delta and United under the following CPAs:</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">CRJ-200 ASA</font>.&#160;&#160;The Company, through its Pinnacle and Mesaba subsidiaries, provides regional jet service to Delta under an Amended and Restated Airline Services Agreement (the &#8220;CRJ-200 ASA&#8221;) that was amended on July 1, 2010 to include Mesaba&#8217;s 19 CRJ-200 aircraft.&#160;&#160;At the end of its term in 2017, the CRJ-200 ASA automatically extends for additional five-year periods unless Delta provides notice to the Company two years prior to the termination date that it does not plan to extend the term.&#160;&#160;The Company subleases its 145 CRJ-200 aircraft from Delta, and Delta reimburses the Company&#8217;s CRJ-200 aircraft rental expense in full under the terms of the CRJ-200 ASA.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA</font>.&#160;&#160;On April 27, 2007, the Company entered into a ten-year CPA with Delta under which Pinnacle operates 16 CRJ-900 aircraft, each for ten years, as a Delta Connection Carrier.&#160;&#160;Delta also has the option to add an additional seven CRJ-900 aircraft under the Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2010, Pinnacle operated 16 CRJ-900 aircraft under the Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA</font>.&#160;&#160;On July, 1, 2010, the Company entered into a 12-year CPA with Delta under which Mesaba operates 41 CRJ-900 aircraft as a Delta Connection Carrier (the &#8220;Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA&#8221;) through June 30, 2022.</font></div>

<br>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<br>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">3.&#160;&#160;Code-share Agreements with Partners (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Saab DCA. </font>Mesaba provides turboprop service to Delta as a Delta Connection Carrier and operated 26 Saab 340B+ aircraft as of December 31, 2010 (the &#8220;Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA&#8221;).&#160;&#160;Delta will progressively retire Mesaba&#8217;s fleet of Saab 340B+ aircraft during 2011.&#160;&#160;Mesaba&#8217;s Saab operations will not extend beyond June 2012.&#160;&#160;As the aircraft exit service, they will be returned to Delta on an &#8220;as is&#8221; basis.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">United Q400 CPA</font>.&#160;&#160;On February 2, 2007, the Company entered into a CPA under which Colgan operates Q400 regional aircraft predominantly out of United&#8217;s hub at Newark/Liberty International Airport.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2010, Colgan operated 22 Q400 under the United Q400 CPA.&#160;&#160;Each aircraft will be operated for a term of ten years from the date each aircraft was placed into service.&#160;&#160;The Company will take delivery of and place into service eight additional Q400 aircraft during 2011.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Under its CPAs, the Company receives the following payments from the major airline:</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: -1pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Reimbursement payments</font>:&#160;&#160;The Company receives monthly reimbursements for certain expenses associated with CPA operations.&#160;&#160;These vary by contract, but typically include: basic aircraft and engine rentals; aviation liability, war risk, and hull insurance; third-party deicing services; third-party engine and airframe maintenance; hub and maintenance facility rentals; passenger security costs; certain ground handling expenses; certain landing fees; and property taxes.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: -1pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company has no direct financial risk associated with cost fluctuations for these items because the Company is reimbursed by the major airline for the actual expenses incurred.&#160;&#160;Under the terms of the CPAs, the major airline partner provides certain supplies and services such as fuel and aircraft rent and ownership costs at no charge.&#160;&#160;As a result, these items are not recorded in the Company&#8217;s consolidated statements of operations.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: -1pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Payments based on pre-set rates</font>:&#160;&#160;Under CPAs, the Company is entitled to receive payments for each completed block hour and departure and a monthly fixed cost payment based on the size of its fleet.&#160;&#160;These payments are designed to cover all of the Company&#8217;s expenses incurred with respect to CPA operations that are not covered by the reimbursement payments.&#160;&#160;The substantial majority of these expenses relate to labor costs, ground handling costs in cities where the partner does not have ground handling operations, overhead, and depreciation.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In connection with the acquisition of Mesaba, the Company modified its existing capacity purchase agreements with Delta to provide for a rate adjustment that will be effective upon the earlier of the date that the Company implements a combined collective bargaining agreement covering both Pinnacle&#8217;s and Mesaba&#8217;s pilots, or the date that the jet operations of Pinnacle and Mesaba are combined under a single operating certificate (the &#8220;Adjustment Trigger Date&#8221;).&#160; This rate adjustment is designed to increase Pinnacle&#8217;s rates commensurate with the increase in pilot labor costs related to Pinnacle&#8217;s Delta operations.&#160; The rate adjustment will be calculated and agreed to by the Company and Delta 12 months after the Adjustment Trigger Date.&#160; At that time, the Company will receive a one-time r
etroactive adjustment related to the prior 12 months for the increase in its pilot costs, inclusive of training and displacement related to the merging of Pinnacle&#8217;s and Mesaba&#8217;s pilot groups.&#160; In addition, the Company will receive a prospective adjustment payable for future periods such that its rates pertaining to pilot costs will be approximately equivalent to its actual pilot costs at the time of the rate adjustment.&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In addition, the rate-based payments the Company receives under its CRJ-200 ASA and its Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA will be adjusted at the beginning of 2013 when a negotiated rate reset will occur.&#160; This rate reset is designed to adjust the Company&#8217;s rate based compensation under the CRJ-200 ASA and the Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA to equal its actual and projected costs (excluding pilot-related costs) under those CPAs at that time.</font></div>

<br>
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>
</div>

<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">71</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%">
<hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
</div>
</div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<br>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">3.&#160;&#160;Code-share Agreements with Partners (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: -1pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Margins, mark-up and incentive payments</font>:&#160;&#160;The Company receives monthly margin or mark-up payments from Delta related to the CRJ-200 ASA, Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA, Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA, and Saab DCA.&#160;&#160;For example, the monthly margin payment for the Company&#8217;s CRJ-200 ASA is calculated based on a target operating margin of 8% on qualifying expenses.&#160;&#160;The portion of any margin payments attributable to reimbursement payments will always be equal to the targeted operating margin for the relevant period.&#160;&#160;However, since the margin pre-set rate payments are not based on the actual expenses incurred, if actual expenses differ from these payments, the actual operating margin on CRJ-200 operations could differ from the target operating margin.&#160;
&#160;Under the Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA, Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA, and Saab DCA, Pinnacle and Mesaba receive monthly mark-up payments calculated as a percentage of certain expenses.&#160;&#160;In addition, Pinnacle and Mesaba are eligible for certain incentive payments based upon operating performance.&#160;&#160;&#160;Colgan is eligible for certain incentive payments under the United Q400 CPA, which are based upon its operating performance.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Deferred revenue:</font>&#160;&#160;After Northwest&#8217;s 2005 bankruptcy, the Company and Northwest entered into an Assumption and Claims Resolution Agreement (the &#8220;Assumption Agreement&#8221;) on December 15, 2006.&#160;&#160;Under the Assumption Agreement, Northwest and the Company agreed that the Company would receive an allowed unsecured claim against Northwest in its bankruptcy proceedings as a result of the renegotiation of the CRJ-200 ASA.&#160;&#160;The Company is recognizing $253,042, the fair value of its stipulated unsecured claim, over the 11-year term of the CRJ-200 ASA.&#160;&#160;The Company expects to recognize non-cash CRJ-200 ASA-related revenue of $23,199 per year in the years 2011 &#8211; 2017.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Under the Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA, the Company defers certain revenue primarily related to maintenance.&#160;&#160;For example, the Company receives monthly payments based on contractual rates per departure and block hour for heavy maintenance activities not expected for at least a year.&#160;&#160;To the extent that the ultimate maintenance costs incurred are less than amounts collected, the Company will refund to Delta the excess.&#160;&#160;Conversely, the Company bears the risk that the maintenance costs incurred exceed the payments generated from the contractual rates.&#160;&#160;The Company defers the revenue related to these maintenance deposits, and will recognize the revenue when it performs the underlying maintenance services.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">As discussed in Note 4, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Acquisition of Mesaba</font>, $5,000 was recorded as deferred revenue as a result of the agreements reached in conjunction with the acquisition of Mesaba.&#160; The Company is recognizing this deferred revenue over 12 years.&#160; In addition, the Company recorded a deferred credit of $3,500 related to the fair value of the Saab DCA, which is being recognized as increases to revenue through December 31, 2011.&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The following table includes the deferred revenue components of the Company&#8217;s various CPAs with Delta:</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Settlement of Disputes with Code-share Partner.</font>&#160;&#160;On July 1, 2010, the Company and Delta reached agreement over a number of significant disputes, primarily related to the Company&#8217;s CRJ-200 ASA, that had arisen since 2007 and that were discussed in the Company&#8217;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2009.</font></div>
