<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<br>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">3.&#160;&#160;Code-share Agreements with Partners (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">One disputed item related to a one-time adjustment to the Company&#8217;s block hour, cycle, and fixed payment rates under the CRJ-200 ASA that was to become effective January 1, 2006.&#160; Delta had asserted that the adjustment should have resulted in a significant decrease in the rates under the CRJ-200 ASA, of as much as $3,000 annually, with a cumulative adjustment of as much as $11,000 from 2006 through June 30, 2010.&#160;&#160;The Company had asserted that the adjustment would have resulted in an increase in the CRJ-200 ASA rates of as much as $3,000 to $5,000 annually.&#160;&#160;On July 1, 2010, the parties agreed to release each other from any claims related to this one-time adjustment, and the rates then in effect under the CRJ-200 ASA were not adjusted.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In early 2010, Pinnacle tentatively agreed to accept Delta&#8217;s treatment of ground handling revenues and costs for all periods after August 1, 2009, without any retroactive application prior to August 1, 2009.&#160;&#160;Pinnacle and Delta also tentatively agreed to stipulate the prospective revenue adjustment under a provision of the CRJ-200 ASA associated with the allocation of Pinnacle&#8217;s overhead upon the establishment of a certain level of operations outside of the CRJ-200 ASA.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The 2010 amendment to the CRJ-200 ASA included a provision to establish this rate reduction through the 2013 rate reset.&#160;&#160;The Company agreed to reduce fixed rates charged to Delta by $2,000 for 2010, $2,500 for 2011, and $2,500 for 2012.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company and Delta also finalized a number of other matters under the CRJ-200 ASA upon which the parties previously had agreed verbally, including the resolution of a dispute related to aircraft paint reimbursements and adjustments to remove landing fees and air navigation fees from the Company&#8217;s fixed rates and convert these expenses into fully reimbursed costs.&#160;&#160;None of these items had a material impact on the Company&#8217;s results of operations for the year ended December 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;For discussion regarding the settlement of aviation insurance premium dispute between the Company and Delta, see Note 4, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Acquisition of Mesaba</font>.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Concentration of credit risk:&#160; </font>As of December 31, 2010, amounts owed from Delta represented 86%, or approximately $34,033, of the Company&#8217;s accounts receivable balance, which is uncollateralized.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Revenue Pro-rate Agreements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The contractual relationships the Company acquired through its purchase of Colgan in January 2007 included revenue pro-rate code-share agreements, which allow Colgan to market its operations under its partners&#8217; brands.&#160; Under these agreements, Colgan generally manages its own inventory of unsold capacity and sets fare levels in the local markets that it serves.&#160;&#160;Colgan retains all of the revenue for passengers flying within its local markets that do not connect to its partners&#8217; flights.&#160;&#160;For connecting passengers, the passenger fare is pro-rated between Colgan and its major airline partner, generally based on the distance traveled by the passenger on each segment of the passenger&#8217;s trip.&#160; Under these agreements, Colgan bears the risk associated with fares, passenger demand, and competiti
on within its markets.&#160;&#160;Colgan incurs all of the costs associated with operating these flights, including those costs typically reimbursed or paid directly by the major airline under a capacity purchase agreement.&#160;&#160;In some instances, Colgan has the ability to earn incentive-based revenue should it achieve specified performance metrics.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Colgan&#8217;s financial performance is also subject to seasonal fluctuations.&#160;&#160;Colgan has historically reported lower unit revenue (as measured by revenue per available seat mile) during the first and fourth quarters each year when demand for air travel declines, and reported higher unit revenue during the second and third quarters each year when air travel demand is higher.</font></div>

<br>
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>
</div>

<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">73</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%">
<hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
</div>
</div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<br>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">3.&#160;&#160;Code-share Agreements with Partners (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">United Air Lines</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">As of December 31, 2010, the Company, through its Colgan subsidiary, operated 13 Saab 340 aircraft based in Houston, Texas under a pro-rate agreement with United (the &#8220;United Houston Agreement&#8221;).&#160;&#160;Colgan entered into the United Houston Agreement in January 2005 for a term of five years.&#160;&#160;In addition to receiving pro-rated passenger revenue as described above under &#8220;Revenue Pro-rate Agreements,&#8221; the Company receives an incentive payment for each passenger connecting onto or from a United flight in Houston.&#160;&#160;These incentive payments adjust every January 1 and July 1 for anticipated changes in the cost of fuel and changes in certain station-related costs over the subsequent six-month period.&#160;&#160;&#160;Since the end of the five-year term in 2010, the Company continues to operate
 under the United Houston Agreement on a month to month basis and is currently in discussions with United about extending this agreement beyond its initial five year term.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">As of December 31, 2010, the Company, through its Colgan subsidiary, operated 11 Saab 340 aircraft based at Washington-Dulles airport under a code-share agreement with United (the &#8220;United Dulles Agreement&#8221;), which expires on December 31, 2011.&#160; In addition to receiving pro-rated passenger revenue as described above under &#8220;Revenue Pro-rate Agreements,&#8221; United pays the Company a set passenger connect incentive fee for certain of the markets that Colgan operates under the United Express Agreement.&#160; The passenger connect incentive may only be adjusted during the three-year term by mutual consent of the parties.&#160; The Company does have the right, however, to cease serving these markets to the extent that its operations are not profitable.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">US Airways</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">As of December 31, 2010, the Company, through its Colgan subsidiary, operated nine Saab 340 aircraft under a pro-rate agreement with US Airways (the &#8220;US Airways Agreement&#8221;).&#160;&#160;<font style="BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ffffff; DISPLAY: inline">In 1999, Colgan entered into the US Airways Agreement to provide passenger service and cargo service under the name &#8220;US Airways Express.&#8221; The current US Airways Agreement became effective on October 1, 2005 under terms</font> similar to the 1999 agreement and had an initial three-year term that automatically extends for 120 day periods unless either party gives notice to the other to terminate.&#160;&#160;The Company and US Airways amended the US Airways Agreement in January 2011 to add service at New York LaGuardia with seven aircraft to be flown by Mesaba.&#160;&#160;Oper
ation of this expanded service will commence in the second quarter of 2011.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Essential Air Service</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In addition to the code-share agreements described above, the Company, through Colgan&#8217;s pro-rate networks, operates under agreements with the DOT to provide subsidized air service to ten communities as of December 31, 2010 as part of the Essential Air Service program.&#160;&#160;Colgan operates in three of these markets under its US Airways Agreement, six markets under its United Dulles Agreement, and one market under its United Houston Agreement.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><a name="FN4">4.&#160;&#160;Acquisition of Mesaba</a></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">On July 1, 2010, the Company entered into a Stock Purchase Agreement (the &#8220;Stock Purchase Agreement&#8221;) with Delta and Mesaba pursuant to which the Company purchased all of the issued and outstanding common stock of Mesaba from Delta (the &#8220;Acquisition&#8221;). The consolidated financial statements reported herein contain Mesaba&#8217;s operating results since the Acquisition date.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company is accounting for the Acquisition in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 805, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Business Combinations</font>, whereby the purchase price paid is allocated to the tangible and identifiable intangible assets acquired and liabilities assumed from Mesaba based on their estimated fair values as of the Acquisition date.&#160;&#160;&#160;In the fourth quarter of 2010, the Company finalized the process of obtaining information to evaluate the acquisition-date fair value of the consideration transferred to Delta, the assets acquired, and the liabilities assumed.</font></div>

<br>
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>
</div>

<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>
</div>

<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; WIDTH: 100%">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">74</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%">
<hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
</div>
</div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">4.&#160;&#160;Acquisition of Mesaba (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The total acquisition-date fair value of consideration transferred to Delta was $75,013.&#160;&#160;This amount is comprised of: 1) a promissory note payable to Delta of $63,265, which is secured by all of the capital stock and certain equipment of Mesaba, pursuant to a security and pledge agreement (the &#8220;Promissory Note&#8221;); 2)&#160;a $5,000 payment to Delta; and 3) $6,748 representing the cancellation of amounts owed to the Company by Delta relating to the reimbursement of past aviation insurance premiums.&#160; The Promissory Note has an interest rate of 12.5%, with the principal payable in equal quarterly installments of $3,163 beginning on October 15, 2010 and a final maturity date of July 15, 2015.&#160;&#160;Payments under the Promissory Note may be made by deductions from amounts due to the Company under all of the C
ompany&#8217;s operating agreements with Delta.&#160;&#160;The Promissory Note with Delta contains cross-default provisions for all of the Company&#8217;s operating agreements with Delta.&#160;&#160;These cross-default provisions are not effective until July 1, 2011.&#160;&#160;The Promissory Note also contains customary covenants and representations, including a covenant to maintain a minimum amount of cash and cash equivalents at the end of each month, and restrictions related to the payment of dividends and repurchase of stock.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">During the second half of 2009, Delta began disputing its obligation to fully reimburse Pinnacle for its aviation insurance premiums under both the CRJ-200 ASA and the Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA.&#160;&#160;In connection with the Acquisition, the Company and Delta signed an agreement whereby, beginning July 1, 2010, all amounts pertaining to aviation insurance premiums under the CRJ-200 ASA and the Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA will be reimbursed in full.&#160;&#160;The cumulative reimbursement shortfall of $6,748 from July 1, 2009 through June 30, 2010 was resolved in conjunction with the Acquisition.&#160;&#160;As this amount was realized in connection with entering into new and amended long-term revenue contracts with Delta, $5,000, which is the amount in excess of the $1,748 receivable previously recorded by Pinnacle, will be deferred and recogn
ized as revenue over 12 years, which is the life of the Mesaba contractual cash flows.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The following table represents the allocation of the total consideration of $75,013 to tangible and intangible assets acquired and liabilities assumed:</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt"><font id="TAB1" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 36pt"></font>The difference between the purchase price and the fair value of Mesaba&#8217;s tangible and intangible assets acquired and liabilities assumed was recorded as goodwill.&#160;&#160;The $3,860 in goodwill has been fully allocated to Mesaba, which is presented as a new operating segment of the Company in Note 5, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Segment Reporting</font>.&#160;&#160;The Company attributes this goodwill to the opportunity to expand its regional airline services and its relationship with Delta as well as the synergies that will be created by operating similar fleet types out of overlapping hub locations.&#160;&#160;The entire goodwill balance from the Acquisition will be deductible for tax purposes. During the three months ended December 31, 2010, the Company r
ecorded certain purchase accounting adjustments during the measurement period, resulting in a $3,057 reduction to goodwill.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<td valign="bottom" width="20%" style="BORDER-BOTTOM: black 4px double; TEXT-ALIGN: right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">9,758</font></td>
<td nowrap valign="bottom" width="1%" style="TEXT-ALIGN: left; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4px"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;</font></td>
</tr></table>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company has included in our consolidated statement of operations for year ended December 31, 2010 operating revenues from Mesaba of $141,382 and operating income of $6,847 for the period from July 1, 2010 to December 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;During the year ended December 31, 2010, the Company incurred transaction costs of $1,486 related to the Acquisition.&#160;&#160;These costs have been recognized in operating expense within the consolidated statement of operations.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The following unaudited pro forma combined results of operations give effect to the Acquisition as if it had occurred at the beginning of the period presented.&#160;&#160;The terms of Mesaba&#8217;s capacity purchase agreements entered into concurrently with the Acquisition have been retroactively applied to the beginning of the periods presented.&#160;&#160;The unaudited pro forma combined results of operations do not purport to represent the Company&#8217;s consolidated results of operations had the Acquisition occurred on the dates assumed, nor are these results necessarily indicative of the Company&#8217;s future consolidated results of operations. The Company expects to realize significant benefits from integrating Mesaba&#8217;s operations into its existing operations. The unaudited pro forma combined results of operations do no
t reflect these benefits or costs.</font></div>

<td align="left" valign="bottom" width="64%">

</td>
<td align="right" valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;</font></td>
<td valign="bottom" width="1%" style="TEXT-ALIGN: left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">$</font></td>

</tr></table>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div align="center">
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="75%" style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr>
<td valign="top" width="3%" style="TEXT-ALIGN: right">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: right; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">(1)&#160; </font></div>
</td>
<td valign="top" width="64%">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">During the year ended December 31, 2009, Mesaba generated additional income by providing ground handling services to various third parties, most of which were related parties.&#160;&#160;This line of business, which typically generated high margins, ended in September 2009 and has been classified as a discontinued operation for the year ended December 31, 2009.</font></div>
</td>
</tr></table>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In connection with the Acquisition, the Company and Delta entered into an amendment and restatement of the Company&#8217;s CRJ-200 ASA, under which it operated 126 CRJ-200 aircraft as a Delta Connection carrier, to add the operation of Mesaba&#8217;s fleet of CRJ-200 aircraft to the agreement.&#160;&#160;The Company and Delta also entered into an amendment of the Pinnacle CRJ-900 DCA, under which it operates 16 CRJ-900 aircraft as a Delta Connection carrier, primarily to conform certain operating performance metrics with new standards established by the Company and Delta related to the combined fleet of Pinnacle&#8217;s and Mesaba&#8217;s CRJ-900 aircraft.&#160;&#160;The Company and Delta also entered into the Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA, regarding the operation of Mesaba&#8217;s 41 CRJ-900 aircraft for Delta, and the Saab DCA, which pertains 
to the operation of Mesaba&#8217;s SAAB 340B+ aircraft for Delta.&#160;&#160;The Mesaba CRJ-900 DCA terminates Junes 30, 2022.&#160;&#160;The Saab DCA, which is structured for the wind-down of Mesaba&#8217;s Saab operations, terminates no later than June 30, 2012.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Mesaba and Delta also entered into a facilities use agreement for Delta to license a back-up operational facility to Mesaba for two years following closing.&#160;&#160;Additionally, Mesaba and Delta entered into a transition services agreement for Mesaba to provide information technology, finance, and human resource administrative services to a subsidiary of Delta for one year following the closing date of the Acquisition.&#160;&#160;Finally, Mesaba and Delta also entered into a mutual release agreement, which terminated most operating agreements previously in place between the parties.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><a name="FN5">5.&#160;&#160;Segment Reporting</a></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Generally accepted accounting principles require disclosures related to components of a company for which separate financial information is available to and regularly evaluated by the company&#8217;s chief operating decision maker (&#8220;CODM&#8221;) when deciding how to allocate resources and in assessing performance.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company&#8217;s three operating segments consist of its three subsidiaries, Pinnacle, Mesaba, and Colgan.&#160;&#160;Mesaba is a new operating segment resulting from the Acquisition discussed in Note 4, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Acquisition of Mesaba</font>.&#160;&#160;Corporate overhead expenses incurred by Pinnacle Airlines Corp. are allocated to the operating expenses of each subsidiary.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><a name="FN7">7.&#160; Investments and Fair Value Measurements</a></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company invests excess cash balances primarily in short-term money market instruments and overnight repurchase agreements.&#160;&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Prior to August 2009, the Company&#8217;s investment portfolio consisted primarily of auction rate securities (&#8220;ARS&#8221;)<font style="BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ffffff; DISPLAY: inline">.</font> &#160;In August 2009, the Company reached an agreement to sell its portfolio of ARS to the financial institution that originally sold the ARS portfolio to the Company (the &#8220;ARS Settlement&#8221;).&#160;&#160;&#160;The ARS Settlement provides that for a period of three years from the date of the ARS Settlement, the Company shall have the right to repurchase all or a portion of the ARS at the same discount to par the bank paid to the Company under the ARS Settlement (the &#8220;ARS Call Options&#8221;).&#160; During the three months ended September 30, 2009, the Company determined the initial fair value of the ARS Call Options and the corr
esponding gain from the ARS Settlement to be $4,078.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">For the years ended December 31, 2010 and 2009, upon redemption of certain ARS by the issuer at par, the Company exercised a portion of the ARS Call Options and received net cash proceeds of $2,636 and $1,288, respectively, and recorded realized gains of $1,132 and $582, respectively.&#160;&#160;The Company determined the fair value of the ARS Call Options to be $1,852 and $2,723 at December 31, 2010 and 2009, respectively.&#160; The ARS Call Options are classified as investments on the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheets.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The fair values of the ARS Call Options were estimated using a discounted cash flow model.&#160; The model considered potential changes in yields for securities with similar characteristics to the underlying ARS and evaluated possible future refinancing opportunities for the issuers of the ARS.&#160; The analysis then assessed the likelihood that the options would be exercisable as a result of the underlying ARS being redeemed or traded in a secondary market at an amount greater than the exercise price prior to the end of the option term.&#160;&#160;Future changes in the fair values of the ARS Call Options will be marked-to-market through the consolidated statement of operations.&#160;&#160;&#160;The Company has determined that its ARS Call Options are classified in Level 3 of the fair value hierarchy.&#160;&#160;During the years ende
d December 31, 2010 and 2009, the Company recorded an unrealized gain of $633 and an unrealized loss of $649, respectively, to adjust the ARS Call Options to their fair values.</font></div>

<br>

<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<br>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">7.&#160; Investments and Fair Value Measurements (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">As discussed in Note 9, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Hedging Activities</font>, the Company utilizes aircraft fuel call options and options to purchase forward interest rate swaps (&#8220;Swaptions&#8221;) in order to manage its commodity price risk and interest rate risk, respectively.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The valuations of these instruments are determined using widely accepted valuation techniques, including discounted cash flow analysis on the expected cash flows of each derivative.&#160;&#160;The Company has classified its derivatives in Level 2 of the fair value hierarchy, as the significant inputs to the overall valuations are based on market-observable data or information derived from or corroborated by market-observable data, including market-based inputs to models, model calibration to market-clearing transactions, broker or dealer quotations, or alternative pricing sources with reasonable levels of price transparency. Where models are used, the selection of a particular model to value a derivative depends upon the contractual terms of, and specific risks inherent in, the instrument as well as the availability of pricing informa
tion in the market. The Company uses similar models to value similar instruments. Valuation models require a variety of inputs, including contractual terms, market prices, yield curves, credit curves, measures of volatility, and correlations of such inputs.&#160;&#160;For the Company&#8217;s derivatives, all of which trade in liquid markets, model inputs can generally be verified and model selection does not involve significant management judgment.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Although the Company has determined that the majority of the inputs used to value its derivatives fall within Level 2 of the fair value hierarchy, the credit valuation adjustments associated with its derivatives utilize Level 3 inputs, such as estimates of current credit spreads to evaluate the likelihood of default by its counterparties. For counterparties with publicly available credit information, the credit spreads over LIBOR used in the calculations represent implied credit default swap spreads obtained from a third party credit data provider.&#160;&#160;However, as of&#160;December 31, 2010, the Company has assessed the significance of the impact of the credit valuation adjustments on the overall valuation of its derivative positions and has determined that the credit valuation adjustments are not significant to the overall valu
ation of its derivatives.&#160;&#160;As a result, the Company has determined that its derivative valuations in their entirety are classified in Level 2 of the fair value hierarchy.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The tables below present the Company&#8217;s assets and liabilities measured at fair value as of December 31, 2010, aggregated by the level in the fair value hierarchy within which those measurements fall.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<td valign="top" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160; </font></td>
<td valign="bottom" width="20%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160; </font></td>

</tr></table>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Included in long-term notes payable are borrowings from Export Development Canada (&#8220;EDC&#8221;) for owned aircraft.&#160; The borrowings are collateralized by the Company&#8217;s fleet of Q400 aircraft and 16 of its CRJ-900 aircraft and bear interest at rates ranging between 3.8% and 6.7% with maturities through 2025.&#160;&#160;Amounts outstanding under these EDC borrowings were $623,818 and $513,462 at December 31, 2010 and 2009, respectively.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">During 2009, the Company completed a $25,000, three-year term loan financing with C.I.T Leasing and funded by CIT Bank (the &#8220;Spare Parts Loan&#8221;). The Spare Parts Loan is secured by Pinnacle&#8217;s and Colgan&#8217;s pool of spare repairable, rotable and expendable parts and certain aircraft engines.&#160;&#160;The interest rate for the Spare Parts Loan is a variable rate, which is indexed to LIBOR (subject to a floor) and was 8.0% and 8.5% as of December 31, 2010 and 2009, respectively.&#160;&#160;During August 2010, the Company and CIT amended the Spare Parts Loan to reduce the interest rate floor to 8.0%, to extend the maturity date until June 30, 2014, to provide for additional borrowings of up to $4,500, and to provide for a prepayment penalty under certain circumstances.&#160; The Spare Parts Loan requires that the Co
mpany maintain a minimum liquidity level at the end of every month. The Spare Parts Loan also has standard provisions relating to the Company&#8217;s obligation to timely repay the indebtedness and maintenance of the collateral base relative to the outstanding principal amount of the borrowing.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2010 and 2009, amounts outstanding under the Spare Parts Loan were $23,977 and $24,215, respectively.&#160;&#160; During the fourth quarter of 2010, the Company drew an additional $2,096, increasing total borrowings under the Spare Parts Loan. The proceeds are being used to finance the initial provisioning of rotable aircraft parts to support the Company&#8217;s Q400 aircraft purchases and general working capital purposes.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">On July 1, 2010, the Company completed the Acquisition of Mesaba.&#160;&#160;The Acquisition was financed by the Promissory Note, which had a balance of $60,102 as of December 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;See Note 4, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline">Acquisition of Mesaba</font>, for more details about the Promissory Note.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pre-delivery Payment Financing Facilities</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In January 2009, the Company amended its United Q400 CPA to operate an additional 15 Q400 aircraft.&#160;&#160;The aircraft began delivering in July 2010 and will continue delivery through August 2011.&#160;&#160;In connection with this amendment, the Company executed a new pre-delivery payment (&#8220;PDP&#8221;) financing facility with EDC for up to $35,600 on substantially similar terms to its previous PDP facilities.&#160;&#160;This instrument has an interest rate indexed to LIBOR, which was 3.2% as of December 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;Amounts outstanding under this facility were $19,337 and $6,937 at December 31, 2010 and 2009, respectively.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Bridge Loan</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">On January 13, 2010, the Company entered into a short-term loan agreement with a bank for $10,000 (the &#8220;Bridge Loan&#8221;).&#160; The Bridge Loan was secured by the Company&#8217;s anticipated 2009 federal income tax refund and had an effective interest rate of 4.5%.&#160; The Bridge Loan was designed to temporarily provide the Company with additional working capital until it received its 2009 federal income tax refund.&#160;&#160;The Company repaid the Bridge Loan in full upon receipt of the 2009 federal income tax refund of approximately $38,000 in late February 2010.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Senior Convertible Notes</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In February 2005, the Company completed the private placement of $121,000 principal amount of 3.25% senior convertible notes due February 15, 2025 (the "Notes").&#160;&#160;If certain conditions were met, the Notes were convertible into a combination of cash and common stock equivalent to the value of 75.6475 shares of the Company&#8217;s common stock per $1 par amount of Notes, or a conversion price of $13.22 per share.&#160;&#160;&#160;During 2009, the Company repurchased $90,021 par value of the Notes for $83,870 plus accrued and unpaid interest.&#160;&#160;The book value of that portion of the Notes at the dates of the repurchase was $85,293.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2009, $30,979 par amount of Notes was outstanding.</font></div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">On February 15, 2010, the holders of the remaining outstanding Notes exercised their option to require the Company to purchase all of the remaining outstanding Notes for cash at a purchase price equal to 100% of their principal amount plus accrued interest.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2010, $0 par amount of the Notes was outstanding.</font></div>

</td>

</td>

</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Capital Leases</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company leases certain aircraft equipment and office equipment under non-cancelable capital leases that expire on various dates through 2013.&#160; Amortization of the assets recorded under the capital leases is included in the consolidated statement of operations as depreciation and amortization expense.&#160; At December 31, 2010, the weighted average interest rate implied in these leases was approximately 8.2%, and the net book value of the assets associated with the capital leases was $2,224. The present value of the future lease payments was $2,295, $1,278 of which was classified as a current liability.&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Build-to-Suit Lease</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In February 2008, the Company&#8217;s recently acquired subsidiary, Mesaba, entered into <a name="jump_exp_2"><!--EFPlaceholder--></a>a build-to-suit lease arrangement for the construction and subsequent leasing of a maintenance hangar in Des Moines, Iowa.&#160;&#160;Mesaba was determined to be the, in substance, owner of the hangar for accounting purposes, and therefore, the hangar was recognized on the balance sheet and the lease was recognized as a financing obligation.&#160;&#160;Upon the completion of construction, the initial lease term is 10 years, with the option to extend the lease for one 10-year term, for which the Company determined an extension to be reasonably assured.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2010, the net book value of the hangar was $8,738 and the related financing obligation was $3,077.&#160;&#160;The implied in
terest rate on the build-to-suit lease is 7.5%.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><a name="FN9">9.&#160;&#160;Hedging Activities</a></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company is exposed to certain risks arising from both its business operations and economic conditions.&#160;&#160;As part of the Company&#8217;s overall risk management strategy, the Company utilizes financial derivative instruments to minimize exposure to unplanned decreases in earnings and cash flows that could be caused by volatility in aircraft fuel and interest rates.&#160;&#160;Financial derivative instruments that are used as part of the Company&#8217;s risk management strategy include aircraft fuel call options, interest rate Swaptions, and interest rate swaps.&#160;&#160;The use of these derivative financial instruments is consistent with the Company&#8217;s risk management objective to mitigate exposure to the variability of future cash flows attributable to potential increases relating to volatility in aircraft fuel pri
ces and interest rates.&#160;&#160;The Company does not hold or issue any derivative financial instruments for speculative or trading purposes.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;</font></div>
</div>

<div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>
</div>

<div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always; WIDTH: 100%">
<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">84</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-ALIGN: center; WIDTH: 100%">
<hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
</div>
</div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">9.&#160;&#160;Hedging Activities (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Aircraft Fuel Call Options</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">As a result of the Company&#8217;s pro-rate code-share agreements with US Airways and United, the Company is exposed to aircraft fuel price risk. The Company purchases aircraft fuel in quantities expected to be used in a reasonable period of time in the normal course of business.&#160;&#160;To mitigate the financial risk associated with short-term changes in aircraft fuel prices, the Company initiated an aircraft fuel hedging program in April 2010, using aircraft fuel call options to manage the price risk associated with forecasted purchases of aircraft fuel utilized in the Company&#8217;s operations.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company does not purchase aircraft fuel call options for trading purposes and is not applying hedge accounting as of December 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;Therefore, these options are recorded at their fair value in the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheet, and any increases or decreases in their fair value are recorded in the consolidated statement of income until their expiration.&#160;&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">&#160;</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">At December 31, 2010, the Company had outstanding fuel call options covering approximately 20% of its expected fuel requirements from January through June 2011.&#160;&#160;These options have an average strike price of $2.80 per gallon, providing financial protection if fuel prices exceed this level on average in any given month.&#160;&#160;The Company may purchase additional fuel call options in the future to help mitigate risk associated with potential increases in aircraft fuel prices. During the year ended December 31, 2010, the Company recorded expense of $423 in aircraft fuel expense related to fuel call options.&#160;&#160;The Company had fuel call options with a fair value of $38 at December 31, 2010, which is included in prepaid expenses and other assets on the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheet.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Interest Rate Swaptions</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company is exposed to interest rate risk from the time of entering into purchase commitments until the delivery of Q400 aircraft, occurring between July 2010 and April 2011, throughout which time the Company will receive permanent, fixed-rate financing.&#160;&#160;To mitigate the financial risk associated with changes in long-term interest rates, the Company commenced an interest rate hedging program in April 2010, utilizing options to purchase forward interest rate swaps.&#160;&#160;These Swaptions provide a hedge for the expected interest payments associated with anticipated future issuances of long-term, fixed-rate debt to finance the Company&#8217;s firm future Q400 aircraft deliveries.&#160;&#160;Interest rate Swaptions give the purchaser the right to enter into a swap at a future date if the strike rate of the Swaption is mo
re favorable than the current market swap rate.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company does not purchase interest rate Swaptions for trading purposes and is not applying hedge accounting as of December 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;The Company records these interest rate Swaptions at their fair value on its consolidated balance sheet, and increases and decreases in their fair value are recorded in the consolidated statement of operations until their expiration.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">At December 31, 2010, the Company had seven outstanding Swaptions to hedge the Company&#8217;s risk related to increases in interest rates applicable to approximately $123,500 of debt the Company expects to borrow.&#160;&#160;The average capped rate for the Swaptions approximates 6.9%.&#160;&#160;If actual fixed rates exceed the capped rates, the Company will exercise its option contracts and receive one-time cash payments based on the market value of the interest rate option contracts when the Q400 aircraft are delivered to the Company.&#160;&#160;If the actual fixed rate is less than the applicable hedged fixed rate at the time of delivery, then each Swaption contract will expire unexercised.&#160;&#160;During the year ended December 31, 2010, the Company recorded expense of $1,629 related to the expiration and change in fair value 
of its interest rate Swaptions.&#160;&#160;These costs are classified as miscellaneous nonoperating expense on the Company&#8217;s consolidated statement of operations.&#160;&#160;The Company had interest rate Swaptions with a fair value of $9 at December 31, 2010, which is included in prepaid expenses and other assets on the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheet.</font></div>

<br>
<div id="PGBRK" style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; WIDTH: 100%; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
<div id="FTR">
<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block">&#160;</div>

<div id="HDR">
<div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 8pt">&#160; </font></div>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">9.&#160;&#160;Hedging Activities (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Interest Rate Swaps</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">To manage long-term interest rate risk for the fixed-rate debt issued in 2008 associated with aircraft the Company received and placed into service in 2008, the Company initiated a cash flow hedging program in 2007.&#160;&#160;The hedging program utilized forward-starting interest rate swaps, which hedged the expected interest payments associated with issuances of long-term debt to finance the aircraft.&#160;&#160; The Company had no unsettled swaps associated with this hedging program at December 31, 2010 and 2009.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">These interest rate swaps were designated as cash flow hedges of the permanent financing that was secured in 2008.&#160;&#160;The remaining hedge-related balance, which is included in accumulated other comprehensive loss, is being amortized into interest expense over the life of the aircraft financing.&#160;&#160;The losses from settled interest rate swaps recorded in other comprehensive income (&#8220;OCI&#8221;), net of tax, within the consolidated balance sheets were $12,964 and $14,858 as of December 31, 2010 and 2009, respectively.&#160;&#160;Included in the total net realized losses from interest rate swaps as of December 31, 2010 are $2,808 in unrecognized gross losses that are expected to be reclassified from OCI into earnings during the 12 months following December 31, 2010.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The following table presents pre-tax losses on derivative instruments within the consolidated statements of operations:</font></div>

</div>

<div align="center">
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="75%" style="FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">
<tr>
<td align="right" valign="top" width="4%">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">(1)&#160; </font></div>
</td>
<td valign="top" width="71%">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">This charge is related to the debt that financed the Q400 aircraft that was destroyed in an accident during the three months ended March 31, 2009.&#160;&#160;The associated debt was repaid during the first quarter of 2009.&#160;&#160;This loss is included in miscellaneous nonoperating expense in the Company&#8217;s consolidated statement of operations for the year ended December 31, 2009.</font></div>
</td>
</tr><tr>
<td align="right" valign="top" width="4%">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="right"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">(2)&#160; </font></div>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" width="71%">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman; FONT-SIZE: 9pt">Derivatives classified as cash flow hedges include interest rate swaps.&#160;&#160;Amounts reclassified from OCI into income are recorded in interest expense within the Company&#8217;s consolidated statements of operations.</font></div>
</td>
</tr></table>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><a name="FN10">10.&#160;&#160;Operating Leases</a></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company subleases its CRJ-200 aircraft and related engines from Delta under operating leases that expire at the earlier of the termination of the CRJ-200 ASA or December 31, 2017.&#160;&#160;The lease agreements contain certain requirements of the Company regarding the payment of taxes on the aircraft, acceptable use of the aircraft, the level of insurance to be maintained, the maintenance procedures to be performed and the condition of the aircraft upon its return to Delta.&#160;&#160;Pursuant to the CRJ-200 ASA, Delta reimburses Pinnacle&#8217;s aircraft rental expense in full.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Colgan also leases eight of its 33 Saab 340 aircraft under operating leases.&#160;&#160;All of these lease agreements will terminate by 2013.&#160;&#160;These aircraft lease agreements generally provide that the Company pay taxes, maintenance, insurance, and other operating expenses applicable to the leased assets.&#160;&#160;The leases require the aircraft to be in a specified maintenance condition at lease termination or upon return of the aircraft.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Mesaba leases its CRJ-900 aircraft from Delta under operating leases that expire June 30, 2022, and leases its Saab 340B+ aircraft under operating leases that expire at various points throughout 2011.&#160; Although the leases stipulate a monthly rental that would be a pass-through cost under the respective CPAs, no payments are exchanged between the Company and Delta for Mesaba&#8217;s CRJ-900 and Saab 340B+ aircraft pursuant to the respective CPAs.&#160; Because the Company has no credit risk associated with these leases, the related expense and reimbursement revenue are presented net in the Company&#8217;s consolidated statement of operations, and the rental amounts are not included in the table below.&#160;</font></div>

<br>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold"><a name="FN12">12. Share-Based Compensation</a></font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The Company grants share-<font style="BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ffffff; DISPLAY: inline">based compensation, including grants of stock options and restricted stock, under its 2003 Stock Incentive Plan, for which 4,152 shares</font> were reserved.&#160;&#160;The shares may consist, in whole or in part, of unissued shares or treasury shares.&#160;&#160;Awards which terminate or lapse without the payment of consideration may be granted again under the plan.&#160;&#160;As of December 31, 2010, the Company had<font style="BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ffffff; DISPLAY: inline"> 898 </font>shares of common stock reserved for issuance under the plan.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">When calculating the expense related to share-based payment, the Company estimates expected forfeitures, option expected life, and other elements that affect the amount of expense recognized.&#160;&#160;The benefits of tax deductions in excess of recognized compensation cost are reported as a financing cash flow.</font></div>

<br>

<div style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Pinnacle Airlines Corp.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">(All amounts in thousands, except per share data)</font></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<br>
<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">12. Share-Based Compensation (Continued)</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Stock Options</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Forfeitures are estimated at the time of valuation and reduce expense ratably over the vesting period. This estimate is adjusted periodically based on the extent to which actual forfeitures differ, or are expected to differ, from the previous estimate.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In January 2010, 2009, and 2008, the Company granted 484, 626, and 284 stock options, respectively, to its executive officers, members of its Board of Directors and certain other employees.&#160;&#160;The option grants vest ratably over three-year periods and expire ten years from the grant date.&#160;&#160;Expense is recognized on a straight-line basis over the vesting period.&#160;&#160;The Company recorded pre-tax compensation expense in the amount of $1,479, $1,438, and $1,443, respectively, related to stock options during the years ended December 31, 2010, 2009, and 2008.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Pre-tax compensation cost yet to be recognized related to non-vested stock options was $1,811 as of December 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;This cost will be recognized over the next 1.8 years. During the years ended December 31, 2010, 2009, and 2008, the Company recorded financing cash flows of $0, $0, and $20, respectively, related to excess tax deductions.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The total fair value of shares vesting during the years ended December 31, 2010, 2009, and 2008, was $1,800, $1,436, and $900, respectively.&#160;&#160;The total aggregate intrinsic value of the options exercised for the years ended December 31, 2010, 2009, and 2008, was $700, $0, and $26 respectively.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The fair value of each option grant is estimated using the Black-Scholes-Merton multiple-option pricing valuation model.&#160;&#160;The application of this valuation model involves assumptions that are judgmental and highly sensitive in the determination of compensation expense.&#160;&#160;The fair value of each option is amortized into compensation expense on a straight-line basis between the grant date for the award and each vesting date.&#160;&#160;The Company does not recognize expense related to forfeited non-vested stock options.&#160;&#160;The Company estimates that 4% of stock options will be forfeited or cancelled before becoming fully vested, which is based on historical experience and its expectations of future forfeitures.&#160;&#160;An increase in the forfeiture rate will decrease compensation expense while a decrease in 
the forfeiture rate will increase compensation expense.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">The risk-free interest rate is measured on the U.S. Treasury yield curve in effect for the expected term of the option at the time of the grant.&#160;&#160;Historically, the Company has not paid dividends nor does it plan to pay any dividends in the foreseeable future.&#160;&#160;The expected term of options granted have a maximum life of ten years.&#160;&#160;The expected life is the period of time the Company expects the options granted to be outstanding.&#160;&#160;The market price volatility of options granted is based on the historical volatility since November 25, 2003, the date of the Company&#8217;s initial public offering.&#160;&#160;The forfeiture rate is based on historical information and management&#8217;s best estimate of future forfeitures.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Restricted Stock</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">In January 2010, 2009, and 2008, the Company awarded 220, 278, and 109 shares, respectively, of restricted stock to certain officers and members of the Board of Directors under the Company's 2003 Stock Incentive Plan.&#160;&#160;Using the straight-line method, these shares are being expensed ratably over the three-year vesting period.&#160;&#160;During the years ended December 31, 2010, 2009, and 2008, the Company recognized $1,250, $1,199, and $1,159, respectively, of pre-tax compensation expense related to these grants of restricted stock.&#160;&#160;Pre-tax compensation cost yet to be recognized related to these restricted stock grants was $1,526 as of December 31, 2010.&#160;&#160;This cost will be recognized over the next 1.8 years.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.2pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">During the vesting periods, grantees have voting rights, but the shares may not be sold, assigned, transferred, pledged, hypothecated or otherwise disposed of, alienated or encumbered.&#160;&#160;Additionally, granted but unvested shares are forfeited upon a grantee&#8217;s separation from service.</font></div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block"><br>
</div>

<div style="TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold">Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements</font></div>
